    <stitle>DT/DTI-466 A and B Series DT/DTI/DTA-466 C Diesel Engine Diagnostics (1993) - ENGINE DIAGNOSTIC TEST
        PROCEDURES - DT/DTI/DTA - 466 C SERIES DIESEL ENGINES - MEASURE SMOKE INTENSITY DT/DTI/DTA-466 C Engines (With
        Robert Bosch "MW" or "A" Fuel Injection Pump) - MEASURE SMOKE INTENSITY
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="1">
        <title>MEASURE SMOKE INTENSITY</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>General Description</title>
            <para>The smoke sampling kit (SE-2580) is used to measure smoke levels at the exhaust pipe at full load and
                rated speed.
            </para>
            <para>The smoke sampling kit (SE-2580) sampling pump draws off a precise amount of exhaust gas from the
                exhaust pipe of the respective engine and then sucks it through a filter paper disk.
            </para>
            <para>The filter paper disk, in turn, darkens during this process and thus gives the measure of the soot
                content of the exhaust gases. The filter disk is then compared to the Bacharach Oil Burner Smoke Scale
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4500652">6.52</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                <emph type="bold">(Chart II)</emph>. The Bosch smoke number is then determined and compared to the
                standards given in the Performance Data Guidelines, in this section.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>WHEN USING THE SMOKE SAMPLING KIT SE-2580 FOLLOW THE INSTRUMENT MANUFACTURERS OPERATING
                        INSTRUCTIONS TO ASSURE ACCURATE READINGS. DO NOT DEVIATE FROM THOSE INSTRUCTIONS.
                    </para>
                    <para>DO NOT COMPARE SAMPLING DISCS WITH THE SMOKE SCALE REPRESENTED IN CHART II. USE ONLY THE
                        ACTUAL BACHARACH SCALE.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <para>Chart II***</para>
            <para>Representation of:</para>
            <figure id="ef4500652" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg6186" filename="../figeg6/EG6186.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.52 Bacharach Smoke Scale</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>***- Chart II compares darkness of filter paper to Robert Bosch Smoke Number.</para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">* - Form specified with latest revision.</emph>
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>International(r) Smokemeter Table For Service</title>
            <para>For those service technicians utilizing other smokemeter testing methods, the International(r)
                Smokemeter Table is used to convert the Robert Bosch number to other common smoke scales.
            </para>
            <para>The other diesel smoke testing methods and scales are:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The Robert Bosch Smoke Number:</para>
                <para>This number is determined by drawing .3 litre of smoke into a cylinder. The smoke is drawn at a
                    uniform rate through a filter paper. The darkness of the paper determines the Robert Bosch number.
                    No adjustment is necessary for stack size.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">End of Line (E.O.L.) Opacimeter</para>
                <para>There are three acceptable E.O.L. opacimeters that can be expected to provide similar results on a
                    given exhaust pipe size.
                </para>
                <seqlist style="alphalc">
                    <item>
                        <para>USPHS (United States Public Health Service) meter.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Wager Portable Smokemeter, Model D-6P.</para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Telonic Berkely Model 200 Portable Opacity Meter.</para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
                <para>These instruments are installed at the end of the exhaust pipe. As smoke passes through these
                    devices, percent opacity is measured.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The percent opacity is dependent on the exhaust pipe exit diameter.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The In-Line, Celesco Model 107 Smokemeter.</para>
                <para>This device is installed in the exhaust pipe line generally in a fixed installation such as on a
                    chassis or engine dynamometer. The Model 107 is for a nominal six inch inside diameter exhaust pipe.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Hartridge Smoke Number:</para>
                <para>This number is determined by drawing a measured amount of smoke into a cylinder. A light passing
                    through smoke measures opacity of sample. No adjustment is necessary for stack size.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
